ğŸ”¶ Problem Statement:
Given a sorted array arr[] and a target value, count the total number of triplets (i, j, k) such that:

arr[i] + arr[j] + arr[k] == target

i < j < k

ğŸ”¶ Example:
Input:
arr = [-3, -1, -1, 0, 1, 2], target = -2

Output:
4

Triplets:

(-3, 0, 1)

(-3, -1, 2)

(-3, -1, 2)

(-1, -1, 0)

ğŸ”¶ Constraints Highlights:
Sorted array.

Expected Time Complexity: O(NÂ²)

Space Complexity: O(1) or O(N) (depends on approach).

ğŸ”¶ Approaches
1ï¸âƒ£ Brute Force Approach
Use 3 nested loops to check every triplet.

Time Complexity: O(NÂ³)

Space Complexity: O(1)

java
Copy
Edit
int count = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (int j = i+1; j < n; j++) {
        for (int k = j+1; k < n; k++) {
            if (arr[i] + arr[j] + arr[k] == target)
                count++;
        }
    }
}
return count;
2ï¸âƒ£ Two Pointer Approach (Optimal for Sorted Array)
Fix i, and apply two-pointer (j, k) to find pairs.

Time Complexity: O(NÂ²)

Space Complexity: O(1)

java
Copy
Edit
int count = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < n - 2; i++) {
    int j = i + 1, k = n - 1;
    while (j < k) {
        int sum = arr[i] + arr[j] + arr[k];
        if (sum == target) {
            count++;
            j++;
            k--;
        } else if (sum < target) {
            j++;
        } else {
            k--;
        }
    }
}
return count;
3ï¸âƒ£ HashMap Based Approach (Alternative Optimal O(NÂ²))
ğŸ”‘ Key Idea:
Fix i.

For every k (from i+1 onwards), check if target - arr[i] - arr[k] is already present in HashMap.

HashMap stores previous elements (i.e., possible j values).

ğŸ”‘ Why i<j<k is automatically handled?
Since k loop moves forward, and map is updated after checking, j will always be before k.

ğŸ”‘ Time Complexity: O(NÂ²)
ğŸ”‘ Space Complexity: O(N)
java
Copy
Edit
class Solution {
    public int countTriplets(int[] arr, int target) {
        int n = arr.length;
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n - 2; i++) {
            Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
            for (int k = i + 1; k < n; k++) {
                int remain = target - arr[i] - arr[k];
                count += map.getOrDefault(remain, 0);
                map.put(arr[k], map.getOrDefault(arr[k], 0) + 1);
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}
ğŸ”¶ Core Learnings:
ğŸ”¥ Fixed pointer + 2 Pointer or HashMap is a powerful combo for such problems.

ğŸ”¥ i<j<k handled implicitly if map update is after checking.

ğŸ”¥ For sorted arrays, Two Pointer is most space efficient.

ğŸ”¥ HashMap approach can be useful even for unsorted arrays (with care).

ğŸ”¶ Interviewer Can Ask Variations:
What if array is not sorted?

What if duplicates are allowed or not?

Return actual triplets, not just count.

Solve for 4-Sum / K-Sum variations.

